>i usually can get a beginning out but i cant follow it up with anything.
If this is your first steps into creative writing and you can't seem to get into the meat and potatoes of what you intend to write, then I recommend the same thing I did to break into writing: the Bulldozer method.

Just fucking smash that shit out regardless of quality or coherency. Get that first draft done. Don't even worry about "Oh, it could be better, I should rewrite that sentence." Fuck that, tell that grammar nazi to hold onto his Schirmmützen until you get through this shit. Put some fucking words down until the end of the chapter/story, whichever is relevant. When that's done, you can finally take a deep breath and start to clean up. That first draft you just finished? Unacceptable to show others unless they're going to help you edit and proofread. You wait until you finish the edited, second draft before you post/upload it at the earliest

Anonymous Fri 30 Mar 2018 03:48:14 No.14855291 Report
Quoted By:
>>14854408
The bitch about writing is there's almost always two polar opposite approaches to every problem, and any mixture of them work depending on who you are. The best advice I can give you is, however you're doing it now, try the opposite.
>Listen to music when you write? Stop. Don't? Start.
>Do you meticulously plan and outline, or are you flying blind? Same story.
>Do you dump and revise or agonize over every sentence?
>And so on
If you're getting stuck, try some part of what you're doing the other way around.

I also recommend eating red meat, traveling, supplementing Gingko or magnesium, and providing yourself psychological prompts that establish when it's time to write as opposed to do anything else. For me, that latter means not putting on my headphones when I sit down at my rig. It could be anything for you. Figure out what triggers your "I'm relaxing now" instincts, and don't do that thing. Writing is great, but, like other hobbies, it's still a sort of work, and you have to treat it that way.

I also suggest using writing as a sort of default activity. If you aren't sure what to do, write. I write waiting for my food at restaurants, I write during commercial breaks, I write on the airplane, etc. If you're waiting for something, you should be writing
